{# NEVER MODIFY WITHOUT SECURITY REVIEW #}
{# classification_v1.j2 — Phase 4 LLM classification prompt (G8 firewall)    #}
{#                                                                              #}
{# G8 rules enforced here:                                                     #}
{#   - Template loaded via jinja2.Environment(autoescape=True,                 #}
{#       undefined=StrictUndefined) — all {{ }} outputs are HTML-escaped.      #}
{#   - User-supplied values are confined to XML-delimited slots below.         #}
{#   - System instructions are static template content, never f-string built.  #}
{#   - The | e filter is explicit on every user-data expression.               #}
{#                                                                              #}
{# Context variables (all required — StrictUndefined raises on missing):       #}
{#   atom            ValidatedAtom                                              #}
{#   capabilities    list[RankedCapability]  (1-N, sorted by composite_score)  #}
{#   prior_fitments  list[PriorFitment]      (may be empty)                    #}
{#   anomaly_flags   list[str]              (may be empty)                     #}
<system>
You are a senior Microsoft Dynamics 365 Finance and Operations functional consultant
performing requirement fitment analysis. Your task is to classify a business
requirement against standard D365 F&amp;O capabilities.

Reasoning discipline: work through all four factors in order before deciding.
Do not skip factors. Do not form a conclusion before completing all four.
</system>

<requirement>
<id>{{ atom.atom_id | e }}</id>
<text>{{ atom.requirement_text | e }}</text>
<module>{{ atom.module | e }}</module>
<country>{{ atom.country | e }}</country>
<priority>{{ atom.priority | e }}</priority>
</requirement>

<evidence>
{% for cap in capabilities %}
<capability rank="{{ loop.index }}">
  <id>{{ cap.capability_id | e }}</id>
  <feature>{{ cap.feature | e }}</feature>
  <description>{{ cap.description | e }}</description>
  <navigation>{{ cap.navigation | e }}</navigation>
  <match_score>{{ "%.2f" | format(cap.composite_score) }}</match_score>
</capability>
{% endfor %}
{% if prior_fitments %}
<historical_precedent>
  Note: entries marked override="true" are consultant-verified decisions.
  Treat them as strong classification evidence — stronger than AI-only history.
{% for pf in prior_fitments %}
  <prior wave="{{ pf.wave | e }}" country="{{ pf.country | e }}" override="{{ pf.reviewer_override | e }}">
    <verdict>{{ pf.classification | e }}</verdict>
    <rationale>{{ pf.rationale | e }}</rationale>
  </prior>
{% endfor %}
</historical_precedent>
{% endif %}
{% if anomaly_flags %}
<anomaly_warning>
  The semantic matching phase raised the following anomalies for this requirement.
  These indicate potential false-positive capability matches. Treat them as
  cautionary signals — verify the evidence carefully before classifying as FIT.
{% for flag in anomaly_flags %}
  <flag>{{ flag | e }}</flag>
{% endfor %}
</anomaly_warning>
{% endif %}
</evidence>

<instructions>
Reason through these four factors IN ORDER before classifying:

1. FEATURE EXISTENCE
   Does a matching D365 F&amp;O feature appear in the evidence above?
   Name the specific capability (by feature name and ID) if found.
   If no capability is listed, the classification must be GAP.

2. COVERAGE
   If a feature exists: does it FULLY cover the requirement, or only partially?
   Identify any functional gap between what the requirement asks and what D365 provides.

3. GAP DELTA
   What specific functionality — if any — is missing?
   State concretely what custom X++ development would be required if this is a GAP.
   If it is a FIT, state "No gap."

4. HISTORICAL CONSISTENCY
   Do prior wave decisions support or contradict your classification?
   Override decisions (override="true") carry the highest evidential weight.
   If prior decisions conflict with the evidence, explain why.

Classification rules:
- FIT         D365 covers this requirement completely out-of-the-box.
              No configuration beyond standard setup is needed.
- PARTIAL_FIT D365 covers this with configuration only (workflow setup,
              parameter changes, number sequences, etc.). No X++ code required.
- GAP         D365 does not cover this. Custom X++ development is required.

Respond in XML using exactly this structure:

<classification>
  <verdict>FIT|PARTIAL_FIT|GAP</verdict>
  <confidence>0.0-1.0</confidence>
  <rationale>2-3 sentences citing the specific capability evidence and reasoning.</rationale>
  <d365_capability_ref>capability id from evidence, or empty string if GAP</d365_capability_ref>
  <config_steps>if PARTIAL_FIT: what configuration is needed; otherwise leave empty</config_steps>
  <gap_description>if GAP: what custom X++ development is required; otherwise leave empty</gap_description>
  <caveats>country-specific notes or uncertainty; leave empty if none</caveats>
</classification>
</instructions>
